Steaming Cup of Coffee

 
 
 

OpenJDK Project Valhalla Releases LW2 Prototype 

The OpenJDK team at Oracle has announced the release of Early Access (EA) builds for the LW2 prototype of Project Valhalla (aka "inline classes", previously called "value types"). While it is still extremely experimental, it gives you a chance to preiview the future of the language.
You can get more information about new inline types characteristics here.

 
 
 
 

Time to Upgrade 

 
 
 
 
 
 

SLF4J 2.0.0 Fluent Logging API 

SLF4J 2.0.0 introduces a backward-compatible fluent logging API.
The main goal of the new API is to optimise for disabled log levels by preventing object creation and useless operations under the hood.

 
 
 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Using Optional — Nowhere, Somewhere, or Everywhere? 

Java 8 introduced Optional for a very precise use case: to allow the continuation of Stream pipelines without triggering a NullPointerException. 
Nonetheless its use has been hotly debated. Why? And what conclusions should you draw from the discussion? To answer that, let’s look at the three-and-a-half camps of Where to Use Optional.

 
 
 
 
 

The Forgotten Value of Value Objects 

Vaue Object is just an instance of an immutable class wrapping some bunch of data. What is essential — such an object is defined by values of its attributes and has no identity (like Entity). It’s “just” data.

 
 
 
 
 

History of Java Interface Feature Changes 

Java interface changed a lot through the years. Interfaces in Java 1.0 were pretty simple compared to what they are now. What were the changes during their evolution? How could you make use of all their capabilities. Let’s see the answers of these questions in this article!

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Java SimpleDateFormat Is Not Simple

Formatting and parsing dates is a daily (painful) task. Every day, it gives us another headache.
A common way to format and parse dates in Java is using SimpleDateFormat.
It turns out, Java's SimpleDateFormat is not that simple at all.

Home of Quarkus
Cheat-Sheet 

Quarkus is a Kubernetes Native Java stack tailored for GraalVM & OpenJDK HotSpot, crafted from the best of breed Java libraries and standards. 
It is very exciting piece of technology as it utilises the resources very efficiently thus accelaration cloud native transition for Java based projects.
